It sounds like you mean in connection with the Golden Rule—how lex amoris (“law of love”) and a non-slavery principle relate to it.

The Golden Rule
The Golden Rule is usually stated as:

“Treat others as you would want to be treated.”

It’s strongly associated with the teachings of Jesus Christ, though versions of it appear in many cultures.

How all three ideas connect
1. Golden Rule → reciprocity
Focus: fairness and empathy

You imagine yourself in another person’s place

If you wouldn’t want to be enslaved, you shouldn’t enslave others

2. Non-slavery rule → minimum boundary
Focus: basic human rights

A clear prohibition: never treat a person as property

This is like the baseline moral rule

3. Lex amoris → highest principle
Focus: active, self-giving love

Goes beyond fairness into compassion, care, and dignity

Not just “don’t harm,” but “actively seek the good of others”

How they build on each other
Think of them as layers:

Non-slavery rule → “Don’t violate human dignity”

Golden Rule → “Treat others fairly and empathetically”

Lex amoris → “Act with deep love in all things”

So:
👉 The Golden Rule explains why slavery is wrong (you wouldn’t want it)
👉 Lex amoris goes further—it calls you to uplift others, not just avoid harming them

Simple way to see it
Golden Rule: “Be fair.”

Non-slavery rule: “Don’t dominate.”

Lex amoris: “Love fully.”

