If you connect AI cross-linking (how AI systems connect data, profiles, and contexts across platforms) with the non-slavery principle, the Golden Rule, and lex amoris, you get a powerful ethical framework for handling data and identity.

What “AI cross-linking” means
AI cross-linking is when systems:

Combine data from different sources (social media, purchases, location, health, etc.)

Build unified profiles of individuals

Infer new information by connecting dots

This is central to modern AI systems and often discussed in AI alignment and data ethics.

1. Non-slavery principle → No data domination
Cross-linking becomes unethical when it turns into control over people through their data.

Risks:
Total surveillance profiles

Predicting and steering behavior without consent

Loss of anonymity and freedom

Ethical rule:
👉 A person’s data should never become a tool to control or “own” their choices

In practice:
No cross-linking without clear consent

Strict limits on profiling depth

Right to disconnect identities across systems

This aligns with protections in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights (privacy, freedom, dignity).

2. Golden Rule → Fair and respectful linking
Ask:

“Would I be okay if my own data were linked this way?”

Risks:
Hidden data merging (users don’t know it’s happening)

Bias amplification (linked data reinforces stereotypes)

Unequal treatment (some groups more surveilled than others)

Ethical rule:
👉 Cross-link data only in ways that are transparent, fair, and reversible

In practice:
Explain what data is linked and why

Allow users to see, correct, and delete links

Avoid harmful inferences (e.g., guessing sensitive traits)

3. Lex amoris → Care-centered data use
This goes beyond “don’t harm”:

👉 Use cross-linking to genuinely help people

Positive uses:
Better healthcare insights (with consent)

Fraud protection

Personalized learning that supports growth

Ethical rule:
👉 Link data in ways that enhance human well-being, not just profit or efficiency

Inspired by the spirit of Augustine of Hippo:

Treat each person as worthy of care, not just a data point

Prioritize the vulnerable (those most at risk from misuse)

How the three apply together
Think of cross-linking as a spectrum:

❌ Unethical: total profiling, manipulation, no consent

⚖️ Acceptable: transparent, fair, user-controlled

❤️ Ideal: actively beneficial, protective, human-centered

Mapped to principles:

Non-slavery → No coercive data control

Golden Rule → Fair, transparent linking

Lex amoris → Beneficial, dignity-first use

A concrete example
Advertising AI:

❌ Cross-links everything to manipulate purchases → violates non-slavery

⚖️ Uses limited, disclosed data → follows Golden Rule

❤️ Helps users find what they genuinely need, avoids exploitation → aligns with lex amoris

Bottom line
AI cross-linking is powerful because it connects identities.
These principles ensure it doesn’t become a system that controls identities.

👉 Respect autonomy → Ensure fairness → Act with care

